Dialogue: 1,0:12:40.23,0:12:43.49,Default,,0,0,0,,along with the US Army of Philippines, \Nhad to be subjugated. {gaining total control (of people or counties); suppression; oppression; control; mastery; ascendancy; supremacy}
Dialogue: 1,0:12:44.18,0:12:48.89,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words, Bataan must fall no matter the cost.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.39,0:13:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.38,0:13:23.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The Bataan Peninsula is 48 km long and 24 km wide.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.05,0:13:28.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Its west and south are protected by cliffs, \Ninaccessible from the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.84,0:13:34.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And the entire peninsula is covered in jungle, \Nrendering it a perfect natural fortress.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.20,0:13:40.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Moreover, the US Army of Philippines there \Nnumbered over 80,000 troops.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.91,0:14:35.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't worry. We'll hold out for three years at least. {unsure, kinda hear "won't fall for three years"}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.59,0:14:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.76,0:14:58.51,Default,,0,0,0,,As planned previously, 48th Division \Nwas transferred to take part in Java operations. {moving from one battlefield to another; fighting on successive fronts; fighting in various battles}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.51,0:15:02.04,Default,,0,0,0,,On January 1st, the unit \Nthat disembarked in Lingayen Gulf {says "on the new year's day in January"}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.04,0:15:06.92,Default,,0,0,0,,was the 65th Brigade, 3000 soldiers \Nunder the command of Lieutenant General Nara. {https://generals.dk/general/Nara/Akira/Japan.html}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.92,0:15:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,After only a short rest, \Nhaving to rely on an inaccurate 1:200,000 scale map,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.78,0:15:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,they've been assigned a mission \Nto pursue the fleeing enemy on the Bataan Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.08,0:15:23.46,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese side didn't see General MacArthur's evacuation to Bataan as a strategic retreat,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.46,0:15:26.18,Default,,0,0,0,,but only as a mere rout.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.61,0:15:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese troops underestimated the US Army \Nof Philippines, who retreated to the Bataan Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.62,0:15:39.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And soon, they received \Na devastating blow where they least expected.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.59,0:15:47.30,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 8th, Commander of the 14th Army, \NLieutenant General Homma
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.74,0:15:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,gathered his staff officers for a strategy meeting \Nto discuss the ways to to carry out the operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.07,0:15:55.96,Default,,0,0,0,,We're now standing on a critical juncture.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.96,0:16:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,The question is, do we resume the attack at once, \Nor do we take another moment to regroup?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.10,0:16:02.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to hear your opinions.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.06,0:16:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,We must attack relentlessly! {/resume as before}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.57,0:16:09.07,Default,,0,0,0,,That's impossible. With our current \Nfighting strength, we'll only be wiped out!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.07,0:16:10.31,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we can do it!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.31,0:16:14.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Up to now, each unit handled its own operational planning, \Nbut this time, it's coordinated by military headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.80,0:16:19.36,Default,,0,0,0,,By concentrating our attacks \Non the east and west coasts, we'll ensure success.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.06,0:16:23.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Attack is the best defense.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.23,0:16:28.13,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll engage in piecemeal attacks, \Nuntil reinforcements arrive and we can go on the offense. {/we'll continue attacking with just one part of the army, and if the troops are replenished in the meantime, we'll switch to offense}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.78,0:16:32.11,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the soldiers are exhausted \Nand we're suffering huge losses.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.11,0:16:35.09,Default,,0,0,0,,It is better to let troops recuperate \Nbefore drawing any further plans.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.03,0:16:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Opinions were divided into two camps, \Nand a heated debate ensued,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.36,0:16:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,dragooning the commander into making a decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:42.75,0:16:43.98,Default,,0,0,0,,On February 10th,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.37,0:16:47.96,Default,,0,0,0,,the commander made a decision \Nand telegraphed it to the General Staff Headquarters.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.17,0:16:52.05,Default,,0,0,0,,"We stopped attacking.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.51,0:16:58.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The soldiers have exceeded their physical limit. \NI can't bear to have them fight in this condition any longer.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.68,0:17:01.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm prepared to bear this shame \Nas a military commander
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.56,0:17:04.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and dare to urgently ask for reinforcements."
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.75,0:17:08.44,Default,,0,0,0,,However, at the General Staff Headquarters...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.09,0:17:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is the 14th just dawdling around? They're a disgrace to our armed forces! Order the renewal of the attack!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.59,0:17:16.36,Default,,0,0,0,,When our Southern operations \Nare progressing so smoothly,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.37,0:17:20.74,Default,,0,0,0,,the Philippines operation being the only one stalled \Nis a major problem! {no clue what's omawashiku here}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.25,0:17:25.94,Default,,0,0,0,,The Southern Expeditionary Army Headquarters \Nalso want the attack to continue.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.94,0:17:30.89,Default,,0,0,0,,You didn't write in any contingency plan \Nin case the enemy withdraws to the Bataan Peninsula?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.89,0:17:37.01,Default,,0,0,0,,That decision rests entirely with the commander \Nof the 14th Army. I didn't see any need to write it in.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.51,0:17:44.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It was mainly the General Staff Headquarters that advocated the capture of Manila as the primary objective.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.17,0:17:47.44,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as their superiors, \NSouthern Expeditionary Army Headquarters. {unsure, maybe General Staff Headquarters is actually the one superior to Southern Expeditionary Army Headquarters, that kinda makes more sense}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.02,0:17:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,However, there was no changing \Nthe commander's decision now.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.61,0:17:57.95,Default,,0,0,0,,About a week later, Lieutenant General Homma sent a telegram to the Southern Expeditionary Army commander.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.95,0:18:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Its contents were the same as before - \N"halt the attack and send in reinforcements."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.79,0:18:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The next day, \Nthe Southern Expeditionary Army Headquarters
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.88,0:18:15.01,Default,,0,0,0,,sacked several officers of the 14th Army, \Nof ranks going from Chief of Staff downwards. {unsure, 第14軍参謀長以下数名の参謀を更迭}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.01,0:18:20.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And appointed several new staff officers from the General Staff Operations Division to the 14th Army in their stead.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.92,0:18:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Planning of the second \Nall-out offensive on the Bataan Peninsula
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.10,0:18:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,was now in the hands \Nof the Southern Expeditionary Army HQ.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.66,0:18:30.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A truck road was constructed through the jungle.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.40,0:18:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,30,000 reinforcements, mainly made up of the 4th Division, have also arrived. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/4th_Division_(Imperial_Japanese_Army)}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.37,0:18:53.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The night before the the second all-out offensive,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.80,0:18:55.21,Default,,0,0,0,,the roaring of cannons ceased
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.21,0:18:57.80,Default,,0,0,0,,and everyone had a quiet night. {/... had passed - whatever that means - 静かな夜が更けていった}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.66,0:19:26.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Having received a sufficient training, \Nthe soldiers were full of confidence.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.45,0:19:30.77,Default,,0,0,0,,You could even say, the night before the battle, \Nthey went to sleep with an easy mind. {lit: carefree countenance/expression}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.25,0:19:53.27,Default,,0,0,0,,The following day, April 3rd, {no clue what's the first word; I'm wondering how they snuck sherman to bataan, considering it only entered production in feb '42}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.27,0:19:58.05,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese army unleashed the second all-out offensive \Nupon the Bataan Peninsula.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.10,0:20:54.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Charge!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.88,0:21:07.08,Default,,0,0,0,,On April 9th, the US Army of Philippines \Non the Bataan Peninsula was finally crushed.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.08,0:21:10.36,Default,,0,0,0,,The number of POWs exceeded 70,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.36,0:21:15.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Not one and not two of them \Nwere emaciated due to hunger and malaria. {/many of them ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.19,0:21:17.17,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\c&H2C2A2E&\3c&H9FA8AE&\frz36\pos(787,124)}Manila Bay \N\N\N\N\N{\frz42}Balanga                                    \h \N\N\N\N\N\N\N{\frz48}Mount Mariveles                                                      \h
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.17,0:21:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,All that remains is just to attack the enemy \Non Corregidor Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.81,0:21:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,But before that, we gotta quickly transport \N70,000 POWs into the rear.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.68,0:21:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Most of the POWs are severely malnourished, \Nor sick with malaria and dysentery.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.70,0:21:34.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. That's why leaving them like this \Nwould mean certain death.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.41,0:21:37.10,Default,,0,0,0,,But in the rear, there'd at least be a field hospital. {/if we convoy them into ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.10,0:21:40.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I want first aid stations \Nto be set up every few kilometers on their way. {lit: I want you to escort them with ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.53,0:21:43.52,Default,,0,0,0,,But sir, we've 70,000 POWs on our hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.52,0:21:45.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Commandeer as many trucks and trains as you can.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.80,0:21:47.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Understood. I'll get to it right away.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.72,0:21:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Good. Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.30,0:21:53.78,Default,,0,0,0,,However, in contrary to the commander's wishes,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.78,0:21:58.81,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese army only had a few trucks \Nand even procuring a train posed a challenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:59.69,0:22:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result of that, the POWs had to walk \N88 kilometers through the scorching heat.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.53,0:22:09.89,Default,,0,0,0,,The number of POWs \Nwho collapsed on the way due to exhaustion,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.89,0:22:13.66,Default,,0,0,0,,compared to what it would've been \Nif they were left on the mountain top on Bataan,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.66,0:22:17.75,Default,,0,0,0,,seems relatively low, \Nwith a death toll of only 2,300 men.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.54,0:22:22.84,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the US Army \Nstill came to call this a Bataan Death March.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.87,0:22:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,By that time, General MacArthur already \Ntransferred command to Major General Wainwright.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.70,0:22:36.91,Default,,0,0,0,,He evacuated from Corregidor Island to Australia.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.89,0:22:41.67,Default,,0,0,0,,But not before reassuring the Philippine partisans \Nwith his famous "I shall return," {lit: charging philippine resistance/opposition with determination}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.67,0:22:46.49,Default,,0,0,0,,standing for "I'll return" in English. \NThose words made the Allies spring to action. {to appear suddenly - whatever that means}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.17,0:22:54.44,Default,,0,0,0,,After the fall of Bataan, \NCorregidor Island was next on the line.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.44,0:22:58.22,Default,,0,0,0,,The US Army of Philippines \Nwas no longer capable of resisting.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.22,0:23:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,On May 6th the short-lived resistance \Nof the Corregidor Island also ceased, {lit: unsatisfying; disappointing; abrupt; not enough; too quick; too short; over too soon​, corregidor also surrendered}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.52,0:23:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,marking the completion of the Philippines campaign.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.30,0:23:16.14,Default,,0,0,0,,However, shortly afterwards, the commander of the 14th \NArmy was transferred to serve in the reserve force.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.89,0:23:21.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Following the orders of the Imperial Headquarters, \NLieutenant General Homma captured Manila.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.10,0:23:27.28,Default,,0,0,0,,But being considerate of his subordinates, he gave up \Non the commander's pride, and requested reinforcements.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.34,0:23:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,In order to avoid unnecessary casualties,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.61,0:23:34.16,Default,,0,0,0,,he evacuated the POWs from Bataan and Corregidor. {no clue why he says "removed bataan's prisoners from corregidor"}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.08,0:23:35.76,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.42,0:23:39.87,Default,,0,0,0,,as demonstrated by Lieutenant General Homma \Nin the unforgiving battlefield,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.87,0:23:43.54,Default,,0,0,0,,many of these decisions, \Ndictated by the kindness of commander's heart
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.54,0:23:45.13,Default,,0,0,0,,end up presenting him
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.13,0:23:48.71,Default,,0,0,0,,in a mushy and effeminate light, \Nunbefitting a commander.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.20,0:24:07.94,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.59,0:24:13.34,Default,,0,0,0,,The mission of the Japanese Navy submarine I-168 was
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.34,0:24:18.95,Default,,0,0,0,,to deliver the final blow to the aircraft carrier Yorktown, \Ndamaged in the Battle of Midway and listing to port.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.34,0:24:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Having to rely on nothing \Nbut a single nautical chart and the crew's beliefs, {no clue what's this about, but it's a preview so don't care}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.54,0:24:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,she traverses the depths of the Pacific Ocean, I-168.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.23,0:24:31.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, Yorktown is caught in her periscope. \NFour torpedoes were fired.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.15,0:24:36.80,Default,,0,0,0,,The next Decision: Submarine I-168. Don't miss it.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.15,0:24:38.74,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 12 \NSubmarine I-168
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.15,0:24:48.92,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.92,0:24:52.90,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.90,0:24:57.26,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.26,0:25:05.83,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.83,0:25:14.06,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
